00:41:27.490 --> 00:41:29.932
really well for him.

00:41:29.932 --> 00:41:31.600
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: Now, if you're
not uploading every

00:41:31.600 --> 00:41:34.480
week, and you just can't get
into that regular cadence,

00:41:34.480 --> 00:41:36.740
this is, again, where you can
use curation to really fill

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:37.980
out your channel.

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:41.050
GoPro, the small camera maker,
does a great job of this.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:43.430
They continually find videos
that other people have made,

00:41:43.430 --> 00:41:46.380
using GoPro cameras, and they
pull them into their channel

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:48.180
by commenting on them.

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:49.340
So this does a couple things.

00:41:49.340 --> 00:41:53.190
It fills their channel feed with
fresh content, every day.

00:41:53.190 --> 00:41:56.220
But it's also providing a
shout-out to the community.

00:41:56.220 --> 00:41:58.860
In the case of the first video
they say, sick edit.

00:41:58.860 --> 00:42:00.280
Thanks for sharing.

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:05.070
It really helps tie the
community together.

00:42:05.070 --> 00:42:06.960
The other thing that you really
need to do, beyond

00:42:06.960 --> 00:42:09.250
creating videos, is engaging
with your audience.

00:42:09.250 --> 00:42:11.520
So in the top left, we see
that Chuck Testa is

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:13.580
continually replying
to comments.

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:16.260
He's on his channel at least
a couple times a week.

00:42:16.260 --> 00:42:19.200
And even if it's just throwing
a "nope" on there to keep

00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:22.630
things on his message and let
viewers know that he's

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:24.770
around-- he didn't just post
these videos a year ago and

00:42:24.770 --> 00:42:26.690
hasn't been back since--

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:28.470
this can be really effective.

00:42:28.470 --> 00:42:30.110
In the bottom right, we
see the Fine Bros.

00:42:30.110 --> 00:42:33.270
They're very popular vloggers
on YouTube.

00:42:33.270 --> 00:42:36.090
And they do a couple interesting
things with the

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:37.840
video down here.

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:41.170
The first is they picked up on
Chuck Testa as a meme, and

00:42:41.170 --> 00:42:42.030
they played off it.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:44.490
So they showed the Chuck
Testa video to kids and

00:42:44.490 --> 00:42:45.700
filmed their reaction.

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:48.660
And they got a couple million
views on this video, being

00:42:48.660 --> 00:42:50.710
inspired by another creator.

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:52.560
But then you also see,
in the blue--

00:42:52.560 --> 00:42:54.220
maybe it's hard to
read the font--

00:42:54.220 --> 00:42:58.190
they ask viewers to submit
suggestions for what videos

00:42:58.190 --> 00:42:59.860
they should create next.

00:42:59.860 --> 00:43:02.970
And this is a very effective
tool, very effective

00:43:02.970 --> 00:43:06.330
technique, to both tell your
audience that you're including

00:43:06.330 --> 00:43:09.020
them, that they get to decide
what content gets created in

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:09.980
the channel.

00:43:09.980 --> 00:43:12.990
And it also improves the odds
that the next video that you

00:43:12.990 --> 00:43:15.760
can create will be relevant to
your audience, because you

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:19.360
have asked them, and they have
given you suggestions.

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:23.100
And then finally, a lot of folks
may think they need to

00:43:23.100 --> 00:43:26.160
get fancy video equipment,
whether it's cameras or

00:43:26.160 --> 00:43:28.540
editing suites, things
like that.

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:31.140
Our suggestion to you is
to just get started.

00:43:31.140 --> 00:43:33.710
We've been designing and
investing a lot in YouTube

00:43:33.710 --> 00:43:37.580
tools, so that even people
shooting with shaky cellphone

00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:40.450
cameras can quickly upload their
content to the site.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:42.760
And we have a lot of free tools
to stabilize, color

00:43:42.760 --> 00:43:44.610
correct, trim.

00:43:44.610 --> 00:43:46.730
So it's much more important
to get started and

00:43:46.730 --> 00:43:47.660
get content on there.

00:43:47.660 --> 00:43:51.930
And the free tools on the site
can make it look fine.

00:43:51.930 --> 00:43:55.300
And then if you're ready, with a
large audience, to invest in

00:43:55.300 --> 00:43:56.850
more sophisticated equipment,
you can do

00:43:56.850 --> 00:43:59.920
that at a later point.

00:43:59.920 --> 00:44:02.680
So finally, just a few resources
for after today.

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:05.710
The Creator Hub is the single
place that you should start,

00:44:05.710 --> 00:44:08.770
if you're looking for all sorts
of links on the various

00:44:08.770 --> 00:44:10.090
things we've talked about.

00:44:10.090 --> 00:44:12.830
We also have a Creator Playbook,
which is 100-page

00:44:12.830 --> 00:44:14.380
PDF you can download.

00:44:14.380 --> 00:44:17.220
And it goes through lots of case
studies, many more than

00:44:17.220 --> 00:44:19.670
we're able to touch on today.

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:21.950
The Trends Dashboard that
we mentioned before.

00:44:21.950 --> 00:44:23.800
And then finally, we have a
special section of YouTube

00:44:23.800 --> 00:44:25.920
just for Developers.

00:44:25.920 --> 00:44:29.060
And for developers, there are
going to be four other talks,

00:44:29.060 --> 00:44:32.000
all but the 4 o'clock
will be here today.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.650
And you could learn all about
the API and lots of other

00:44:35.650 --> 00:44:38.440
great ways of using YouTube
in your own

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:40.920
applications and sites.

00:44:40.920 --> 00:44:44.660
So final word goes to Chuck
Testa, who wants to remind you

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:47.250
to make content and
not commercials.

00:44:47.250 --> 00:44:49.470
Hopefully, we gave you guys
some great ideas.

00:44:49.470 --> 00:44:52.310
And we really want you to get
going and start creating

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:55.640
videos and connecting with
your users in the world

00:44:55.640 --> 00:44:57.490
through video content.

00:44:57.490 --> 00:44:58.650
Thanks for coming.

00:44:58.650 --> 00:45:01.490
And now we'll open it
up for questions.

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:05.640
And anyone who asks a question
gets a fancy YouTube sock,

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:09.580
also known as a Tube sock, which
is also very important

00:45:09.580 --> 00:45:11.190
to wear while you're
filming videos.

