00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:38.890
AUDIENCE: So let's say I have
this great YouTube video, and

00:45:38.890 --> 00:45:42.270
I want to reach out
to my audience.

00:45:42.270 --> 00:45:46.730
What are the things I should do
after I create the video?

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:48.305
What should I do next?

00:45:48.305 --> 00:45:51.390
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: So merely
uploading a video to YouTube

00:45:51.390 --> 00:45:53.480
may not be enough, especially if
you don't yet have a lot of

00:45:53.480 --> 00:45:55.090
subscribers to your channel.

00:45:55.090 --> 00:45:56.820
So we encourage you to
do a few things.

00:45:56.820 --> 00:46:00.100
The first is share the video on
social networks, Google+,

00:46:00.100 --> 00:46:01.580
Facebook, Twitter.

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:03.900
In fact, you can connect all
those accounts to your YouTube

00:46:03.900 --> 00:46:07.930
account and automatically have
your content syndicated to all

00:46:07.930 --> 00:46:09.870
those platforms.

00:46:09.870 --> 00:46:13.570
And then find channels that
might find your video relevant

00:46:13.570 --> 00:46:15.020
and communicate with them.

00:46:15.020 --> 00:46:16.900
They usually have their contact
information somewhere

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:18.990
on their channel page,
so reach out to them.

00:46:18.990 --> 00:46:20.800
Say, hey, here's a new
video I created.

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:23.230
Are you willing to feature
me in your channel?

00:46:23.230 --> 00:46:27.750
A more advanced approach is to
do a collaboration, where you

00:46:27.750 --> 00:46:30.160
create a video together with
them, and it gets featured on

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:34.320
their channel and shown to
their large audience.

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:35.570
Thank you.

00:46:38.077 --> 00:46:40.390
AUDIENCE: So after you get
started, and you've got a

00:46:40.390 --> 00:46:43.240
number of communities together,
and a number of

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:45.835
people adding their
videos to it.

00:46:45.835 --> 00:46:48.110
If you get some negative videos,
do you have, as your

00:46:48.110 --> 00:46:50.780
channel owner, the ability
to block or take

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:52.905
those videos down?

00:46:52.905 --> 00:46:54.810
AJ CRANE: You don't have
the ability to block

00:46:54.810 --> 00:46:58.200
user-generated content that
might be about your brand,

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:02.420
uploaded by someone else, unless
it contains copyrighted

00:47:02.420 --> 00:47:05.070
material that you own
the rights to.

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:07.140
But in general--

00:47:07.140 --> 00:47:08.050
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: What
you include in your

00:47:08.050 --> 00:47:09.350
channel is up to you.

00:47:09.350 --> 00:47:12.580
So the playlist that you create
and the things that you

00:47:12.580 --> 00:47:16.130
comment on and add into your
channel is your explicit

00:47:16.130 --> 00:47:17.060
action to do that.

00:47:17.060 --> 00:47:21.140
So you don't have to include
any negative videos

00:47:21.140 --> 00:47:21.830
that are out there.

00:47:21.830 --> 00:47:25.700
AJ CRANE: And another idea is
to include a video response.

00:47:25.700 --> 00:47:28.610
So if someone has created a
negative video, you could do a

00:47:28.610 --> 00:47:30.770
video response and try
and turn it around.

00:47:40.350 --> 00:47:43.470
AUDIENCE: Yeah, for actually
monetizing the video itself,

00:47:43.470 --> 00:47:45.220
if you're making an
entertainment video, not

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:48.360
necessarily an advertisement
for the product that you're

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:51.425
doing, what would you suggest
be good ideas for monetizing

00:47:51.425 --> 00:47:52.840
the video itself?

00:47:52.840 --> 00:47:55.180
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: So a
very timely question.

00:47:55.180 --> 00:47:57.720
We have the YouTube
Partner Program.

00:47:57.720 --> 00:48:01.470
Partners are video creators
who monetize on the site.

00:48:01.470 --> 00:48:04.590
And we're now opening that
up to just about anyone.

00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:07.350
So as long as your account is in
good standing, meaning you

00:48:07.350 --> 00:48:09.590
haven't violated the terms of
service of the site, you're

00:48:09.590 --> 00:48:13.640
not uploading pirated material,
then you can go into

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:16.570
your video manager, opt in to
become a YouTube Partner.

00:48:16.570 --> 00:48:20.580
And we will start sharing
revenue with you right away.

00:48:20.580 --> 00:48:22.327
So I encourage you to
look into that.

00:48:25.309 --> 00:48:28.970
AUDIENCE: Similar question,
like the previous one.

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:31.840
Except become the YouTube
partner, or as a YouTube

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:38.310
Partner, can I use the space as
an advertisement, like in

00:48:38.310 --> 00:48:40.976
the design or somewhere?

00:48:40.976 --> 00:48:42.280
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: You mean the
background around the--

00:48:42.280 --> 00:48:43.330
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the bar.

00:48:43.330 --> 00:48:47.580
AJ CRANE: So it's against out
terms of service to sell your

00:48:47.580 --> 00:48:51.160
background image or your
annotations to an advertiser.

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:54.870
But you can use those as
supported branding or

00:48:54.870 --> 00:48:59.045
value-add to whoever might
be your sponsor.

00:48:59.045 --> 00:49:00.305
AUDIENCE: That's possible?

00:49:00.305 --> 00:49:03.770
As a supported value-add
it is OK?

00:49:03.770 --> 00:49:05.350
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: As long
as it's not technically

00:49:05.350 --> 00:49:07.290
advertising.

00:49:07.290 --> 00:49:09.160
But the most effective
advertising on YouTube is

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:10.070
video advertising.

00:49:10.070 --> 00:49:11.900
That has the highest CPMs.

00:49:11.900 --> 00:49:14.310
And so the pre-rolls in front
of the videos are what make

00:49:14.310 --> 00:49:16.200
the most money.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:18.950
And if you become a YouTube
partner, and you opt into that

00:49:18.950 --> 00:49:21.695
ad format, that's how to best
monetize your content.

00:49:21.695 --> 00:49:24.470
AUDIENCE: One more question,
then [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:24.470 --> 00:49:26.960
So regarding the video
advertisement, can I select my

00:49:26.960 --> 00:49:29.572
own videos for that?

00:49:29.572 --> 00:49:30.934
AJ CRANE: For?

00:49:30.934 --> 00:49:32.390
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: For the ads?

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:33.730
AUDIENCE: Yeah, for ads.

00:49:33.730 --> 00:49:33.973
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: No.

00:49:33.973 --> 00:49:35.270
So we use AdWords for video.

00:49:35.270 --> 00:49:36.900
It's an auction.

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:39.710
And it finds the highest
monetizing and most relevant

00:49:39.710 --> 00:49:41.310
videos for the audience.

00:49:41.310 --> 00:49:43.360
And it may be different
for different people

00:49:43.360 --> 00:49:44.110
watching your video.

00:49:44.110 --> 00:49:46.780
For example, if they're from a
different country, or if they

00:49:46.780 --> 00:49:49.740
have different interests, based
on their watch history,

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:51.910
we may serve up different ads.

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:56.420
And that system tries to
optimize both the advertising

00:49:56.420 --> 00:49:58.240
revenue and the user
experience.

00:49:58.240 --> 00:49:59.437
AUDIENCE: OK, thanks.

00:49:59.437 --> 00:50:01.922
DROR SHIMSHOWITZ: Thank you.

